Theory and research on biological, cognitive, social, and cultural influences on behavioral development from age five years until late adolescence.
Graduate standing; basic biology or physiology, and at least two upper division or graduate level courses in psychology or related fields.

Overview of qualitative and quantitative approaches to empirical inquiry in the social sciences, with a focus on theory and research methods in biological growth and cognitive and social/emotional development from prenatal period to death.
STA 013 or STA 013Y;  Or the equivalent and at least two upper division courses in Human Biology or Developmental Psychology.
Supervising instructors lead research discussions with their graduate students. Research papers are reviewed and project proposals are presented and evaluated. May be repeated for credit.
Individually designed supervised internship, off campus, in community or institutional setting.  Developed with advice of faculty mentor.
Consent of faculty (internship sponsor) and satisfactory completion of placement relevant course work, for example: EDU 213, EDU 216; HDE 222, HDE 242; LAW 272, LAW 273.
